To generate the r*hplus, r*hcross, the kick velocity, and the
total energy and angular momentum radiated in GWs you have to 
take the following steps. 

1) Compile the two files:ccc_ffi_hplus_hcross_ejkick.f90,  gw_fluxes_thru_rect_surfaces.f90 say by typing on our machines

ifort -o rhphc ccc_ffi_hplus_hcross_ejkick.f90
ifort -o flux gw_fluxes_thru_rect_surfaces.f90
or
gfortran -ffree-line-length-512 ccc_ffi_hplus_hcross_ejkick.f90  -o rhphc

so now the executables are names rhphc and flux. Based on the names of the executables
you now can tell that rhphc calculates the plus and cross GW polarizations
multiplied by r, while flux calculates the total J and E radiated in GWs. Lets 
see how we can do that using these executables

2) After running your code you should have the raw Psi4 files. Lets assume that 
you want to use the file called Psi4_rad.mon.3. First thing you have to do is to 
sort this file so that all lines are different and they are listed in the correct
time-order. To do this type

tail -n +2 Psi4_rad.mon.3 | sort -k1 -g -u > Psi4_rad.mon_sorted.3

The tail command removes the header from Psi4_rad.mon.3.
The code is not going to work, if your final sorted file has a header.

Now you have the Psi4_rad.mon_sorted.3 that you can work on. 

3) Go to the file ccc_ffi.input and edit the entries

psi4 filename: This should be Psi4_rad.mon_sorted.3 in our case

number of columns: leave this unchanged (47)

w_lower_cut: should be equal or less than the initial orbital angular velocity Omega.
For NSNS you should set this to ~ Omega or just ~ 0.5*Omega.
For BHBH (puncture ID) you should set this to ~ Madm*Omega or just ~ 0.5*Madm*Omega.
Note that in the puncture ID Madm=1.

***************************************************************************************
*** Note ***: this is NOT the MOmega or a little larger than this!!!
***
*** In Christian Reisswig and Denis Pollney, Class. Quantum Grav. 28 (2011) 195015,  
*** page 16, omega_0 ~ 1.4*omega_orbital = ~ 0.7*omega_gw
*** but the omega_0 is NOT our w_lower_cut.
*** In file ccc_ffi_hplus_hcross_ejkick.f90 we read:
*** Note: The parameter w_lower_cut refers to the *orbital* frequency in code unit, 
***       not the (2,2) mode of GW frequency.
***
*** From code: omega_0 = gw_lower_cut = max(abs(m_gw)*w_lower_cut,w_lower_cut)
***                                   = 2*w_lower_cut  (for m=2)
***
*** If w_lower_cut=1.0*omega_orbital then omega_0=2.0*omega_orbital =Omega22 which is fine  => used in the paper
*** If w_lower_cut=0.5*omega_orbital then omega_0=1.0*omega_orbital <Omega22 which is fine
*** If w_lower_cut=1.5*omega_orbital then omega_0=3.0*omega_orbital >Omega22 which is not good
***
*** Thus w_lower_cut = 1.0*omega_orbital or less (0.5*omega_orbital)  so that
*** Thus gw_lower_cut = 2.0*omega_orbital or less (1.4*omega_orbital)  
***************************************************************************************

Madm: set it equal to the ADM mass

tstart: this is the initial time in Psi4_rad.mon_sorted.3

tend: this must be at most the last time in Psi4_rad.mon_sorted.3

4) Type 

./rhphc 

5) You should now have a bunch of files: ejv_GW.dat omega22.dat rhphc.dat times.dat rhphcdot.dat

rhphc.dat contains the gravitational waveforms r*hplus and r*hcross vs retarted time (column 1)

The file ejv_GW.dat has the total E_GW and J_GW (columns 2,3 respectively) as well as the kick velocity vs retarted time (column 1).

However, ejv_GW.dat does not account for the fact that the domain is actually a square and not a sphere. To calculate
the total E_GW, J_GW accounting for the fact that our computational domains are square you follow the next steps.

6) Edit the entries in the file gw_flux.input

rhphc_filename: is the file rhphc.dat that has been generated by running ./rhphc

rhphcdot_filename: is the file rhphcdo.dat that has been generated by running ./rhphc

Madm, tstart and tend are the same as in the ccc_ffi.input file

delta_t: is the time step in your rhphc.dat file

number of gw modes: leave this unchanged (21)

xmin, ymin, zmin, xmax, ymax, zmax the ones that correspond to your outermost refinement level. 
Note the zmin = -zmax if your are using equatorial symmetry.

nx, ny, nz : Are the number of points for the numerical integration to get the fluxes. Typical values
of 40 x 40 x 40 should suffice. 


7) Given gw_flux.input has been edited type

./flux

8) You should now have the file EJ_rect.dat, which has the correct E_GW and J_GW (columns 2,3 resp.) 
vs retarded time (column 1). Note that in general the E_GW and J_GW in file EJ_rect.dat, should not be
very different from EJ_rect.dat in file ejv_GW.dat (which was generated using the assumption that the domain 
is a sphere).

9) THE END

